WEBVTT

00:00:18.500 --> 00:00:25.620
How to Live on Twenty-Four Hours a Day by Arnold Bennett, Preface.

00:00:28.420 --> 00:00:34.160
This preface, though placed at the beginning as a preface must be, should be read at the

00:00:34.160 --> 00:00:34.900
end of the book.

00:00:35.560 --> 00:00:41.160
I have received a large amount of correspondence concerning this small work, and many reviews

00:00:41.160 --> 00:00:45.380
of it, some of them nearly as long as the book itself, have been printed.

00:00:46.220 --> 00:00:49.120
But scarcely any of the comment has been adverse.

00:00:49.900 --> 00:00:55.500
Some people have objected to a frivolity of tone, but as the tone is not, in my opinion,

00:00:55.500 --> 00:01:01.320
at all frivolous, this objection did not impress me, and had no weightier reproach

00:01:01.320 --> 00:01:06.120
been put forward, I might almost have been persuaded that the volume was flawless.

00:01:07.140 --> 00:01:13.040
A more serious stricture has, however, been offered, not in the press, but by sundry,

00:01:13.220 --> 00:01:17.080
obviously sincere correspondence, and I must deal with it.

00:01:17.440 --> 00:01:23.080
A reference to page forty-three will show that I anticipated and feared this disapprobation.

00:01:23.520 --> 00:01:27.040
The sentence against which protests have been made is as follows.

00:01:28.800 --> 00:01:34.900
In the majority of instances he, the typical man, does not precisely feel a passion for

00:01:34.900 --> 00:01:35.740
his business.

00:01:36.180 --> 00:01:38.500
At best he does not dislike it.

00:01:38.880 --> 00:01:44.860
He begins his business functions with some reluctance, as late as he can, and he ends

00:01:44.860 --> 00:01:47.960
them with joy, as early as he can.

00:01:47.960 --> 00:01:53.960
And his engines, while he is engaged in his business, are seldom at their full horsepower.

00:01:55.920 --> 00:02:03.600
I am assured, in accents of unmistakable sincerity, that there are many businessmen, not merely

00:02:03.600 --> 00:02:09.980
those in high positions or with fine prospects, but modest subordinates with no hope of ever

00:02:09.980 --> 00:02:16.000
being much better off, who do enjoy their business functions, who do not shirk them,

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:20.740
who do not arrive at their office as late as possible and depart as early as possible,

00:02:21.100 --> 00:02:26.860
who, in a word, put the whole of their force into their day's work, and are genuinely

00:02:26.860 --> 00:02:28.780
fatigued at the end thereof.

00:02:29.560 --> 00:02:31.320
I am ready to believe it.

00:02:31.500 --> 00:02:32.880
I do believe it.

00:02:33.080 --> 00:02:34.260
I know it.

00:02:34.440 --> 00:02:35.740
I always knew it.

00:02:36.100 --> 00:02:41.640
Both in London and in the provinces it has been my lot to spend long years in subordinate

00:02:41.640 --> 00:02:47.680
situations of business, and the fact did not escape me that a certain proportion of my

00:02:47.680 --> 00:02:53.520
peers showed what amounted to an honest passion for their duties, and that while engaged in

00:02:53.520 --> 00:02:59.240
those duties they were really living to the fullest extent of which they were capable.

00:02:59.860 --> 00:03:05.620
But I remained convinced that these fortunate and happy individuals, happier perhaps than

00:03:05.620 --> 00:03:12.160
they guessed, did not and do not constitute a majority, or anything like a majority.

00:03:12.860 --> 00:03:18.380
I remained convinced that the majority of decent average conscientious men of business,

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:25.840
men with aspirations and ideals, do not as a rule go home of a night genuinely tired.

00:03:26.380 --> 00:03:33.540
I remained convinced that they put not as much but as little of themselves as they conscientiously

00:03:34.390 --> 00:03:40.700
into the earning of a livelihood, and that their vocation bores rather than interests

00:03:40.700 --> 00:03:41.240
them.

00:03:42.680 --> 00:03:48.720
Nevertheless, I admit that the minority is of sufficient importance to merit attention,

00:03:48.990 --> 00:03:53.420
and that I ought not to have ignored it so completely as I did do.

00:03:53.960 --> 00:03:59.660
The whole difficulty of the hard-working minority was put in a single colloquial sentence by

00:03:59.660 --> 00:04:01.040
one of my correspondents.

00:04:01.380 --> 00:04:09.120
He wrote, I am just as keen as anyone on doing something to exceed my program, but allow

00:04:09.120 --> 00:04:15.760
me to tell you that when I get home at six-thirty p.m. I am not anything like so fresh as you

00:04:15.760 --> 00:04:16.740
seem to imagine.

00:04:18.640 --> 00:04:24.160
Now I must point out that the case of the minority, who throw themselves with passion

00:04:24.160 --> 00:04:30.720
and gusto into their daily business task, is infinitely less deplorable than the case

00:04:30.720 --> 00:04:36.520
of the majority, who go half-heartedly and feebly through their official day.

00:04:37.400 --> 00:04:40.500
The former are less in need of advice how to live.

00:04:41.120 --> 00:04:47.260
At any rate, during their official day of, say, eight hours, they are really alive.

00:04:47.880 --> 00:04:51.300
Their engines are giving the full indicated horsepower.

00:04:52.180 --> 00:04:57.760
The other eight working hours of their day may be badly organized or even frittered away,

00:04:57.760 --> 00:05:03.900
but it is less disastrous to waste eight hours a day than sixteen hours a day.

00:05:04.140 --> 00:05:08.540
It is better to have lived a bit than never to have lived at all.

00:05:09.400 --> 00:05:15.640
The real tragedy is the tragedy of the man who is braced to an effort neither in the

00:05:15.640 --> 00:05:20.580
office nor out of it, and to this man this book is primarily addressed.

00:05:21.300 --> 00:05:28.460
But, says the other and more fortunate man, although my ordinary program is bigger than

00:05:28.460 --> 00:05:31.720
his, I want to exceed my program too.

00:05:32.260 --> 00:05:33.640
I am living a bit.

00:05:33.800 --> 00:05:35.220
I want to live more.

00:05:35.760 --> 00:05:40.460
But I really can't do another day's work on the top of my official day.

00:05:41.940 --> 00:05:48.260
The fact is, I, the author, ought to have foreseen that I should appeal most strongly

00:05:48.260 --> 00:05:51.120
to those who already had an interest in existence.

00:05:51.880 --> 00:05:56.020
It is always the man who has tasted life who demands more of it.

00:05:56.420 --> 00:06:01.740
And it is always the man who never gets out of bed who is the most difficult to rouse.

00:06:02.580 --> 00:06:08.620
Well, you of the minority, let us assume that the intensity of your daily money-getting

00:06:08.620 --> 00:06:13.220
will not allow you to carry out quite all the suggestions in the following pages.

00:06:14.320 --> 00:06:16.780
Some of the suggestions may yet stand.

00:06:17.440 --> 00:06:23.960
I admit that you may not be able to use the time spent on the journey home at night, but

00:06:23.960 --> 00:06:29.480
the suggestion for the journey to the office in the morning is as practicable for you as

00:06:29.480 --> 00:06:30.320
for anybody.

00:06:31.080 --> 00:06:37.520
And that weekly interval of forty hours, from Saturday to Monday, is yours just as much

00:06:37.520 --> 00:06:43.260
as the other man's, though a slight accumulation of fatigue may prevent you from employing

00:06:43.260 --> 00:06:45.820
the whole of your horsepower upon it.

00:06:46.820 --> 00:06:52.240
There remains, then, the important portion of the three or more evenings a week.

00:06:52.960 --> 00:06:58.760
You tell me flatly that you are too tired to do anything outside your program at night,

00:06:59.440 --> 00:07:05.760
in reply to which I tell you flatly that if your ordinary day's work is thus exhausting,

00:07:06.500 --> 00:07:10.480
then the balance of your life is wrong and must be adjusted.

00:07:11.260 --> 00:07:16.400
A man's powers ought not to be monopolized by his ordinary day's work.

00:07:17.240 --> 00:07:19.500
What then is to be done?

00:07:20.240 --> 00:07:26.480
The obvious thing to do is to circumvent your ardor for your ordinary day's work by a ruse.

00:07:27.340 --> 00:07:33.260
Employ your engines in something beyond the program before and not after you employ them

00:07:33.260 --> 00:07:34.700
on the program itself.

00:07:35.660 --> 00:07:38.800
Briefly, get up earlier in the morning.

00:07:39.380 --> 00:07:40.800
You say you cannot.

00:07:41.440 --> 00:07:45.340
You say it is impossible for you to go earlier to bed of a night.

00:07:45.800 --> 00:07:48.380
To do so would upset the entire household.

00:07:49.120 --> 00:07:53.200
I do not think it is quite impossible to go to bed earlier at night.

00:07:53.780 --> 00:08:00.340
I think that if you persist in rising earlier, and the consequence's insufficiency of sleep,

00:08:00.960 --> 00:08:03.720
you will soon find a way of going to bed earlier.

00:08:04.300 --> 00:08:11.180
But my impression is that the consequences of rising earlier will not be an insufficiency of sleep.

00:08:11.860 --> 00:08:20.200
My impression, growing stronger every year, is that sleep is partly a matter of habit and of slackness.

00:08:20.600 --> 00:08:28.360
I am convinced that most people sleep as long as they do because they are at a loss for any other diversion.

00:08:29.140 --> 00:08:35.400
How much sleep do you think is daily obtained by the powerful, healthy man who daily rattles up your street

00:08:35.400 --> 00:08:37.900
in charge of Carter Patterson's van?

00:08:38.600 --> 00:08:41.120
I have consulted a doctor on this point.

00:08:41.760 --> 00:08:49.440
He is a doctor who, for twenty-four years, has had a large general practice in a large flourishing suburb of London,

00:08:50.020 --> 00:08:53.260
inhabited by exactly such people as you and me.

00:08:53.800 --> 00:08:56.720
He is a curt man, and his answer was curt.

00:08:57.420 --> 00:09:00.820
Most people sleep themselves stupid.

00:09:02.360 --> 00:09:08.780
He went on to give his opinion that nine men out of ten would have better health and more fun out of life

00:09:08.780 --> 00:09:10.980
if they spent less time in bed.

00:09:12.420 --> 00:09:19.060
Other doctors have confirmed this judgment, which, of course, does not apply to growing youths.

00:09:19.060 --> 00:09:28.380
Rise an hour, an hour and a half, or even two hours earlier, and, if you must, retire earlier when you can.

00:09:29.060 --> 00:09:36.200
In the matter of exceeding programs, you will accomplish as much in one morning hour as in two evening hours.

00:09:36.840 --> 00:09:42.700
But, you may say, I couldn't begin without some food and servants.

00:09:43.440 --> 00:09:52.000
Surely, my dear sir, in an age when an excellent spirit-lamp, including a saucepan, can be bought for less than a shilling,

00:09:52.320 --> 00:09:59.900
you are not going to allow your highest welfare to depend upon the precarious immediate cooperation of a fellow creature.

00:10:01.140 --> 00:10:05.820
Instruct the fellow creature, whoever she may be, at night.

00:10:06.800 --> 00:10:09.840
Tell her to put a tray in a suitable position overnight.

00:10:10.400 --> 00:10:16.960
On that tray, two biscuits, a cup and saucer, a box of matches and a spirit-lamp.

00:10:17.440 --> 00:10:19.440
On the lamp, the saucepan.

00:10:19.820 --> 00:10:24.540
On the saucepan, the lid, but turned the wrong way up.

00:10:25.120 --> 00:10:31.520
On the reversed lid, the small teapot, containing a minute quantity of tea leaves.

00:10:32.200 --> 00:10:34.300
You will then have to strike a match.

00:10:34.580 --> 00:10:35.420
That is all.

00:10:35.900 --> 00:10:41.820
In three minutes the water boils and you pour it into the teapot, which is already warm.

00:10:42.420 --> 00:10:45.140
In three more minutes the tea is infused.

00:10:45.620 --> 00:10:48.000
You can begin your day while drinking it.

00:10:48.420 --> 00:10:54.280
These details may seem trivial to the foolish, but to the thoughtful they will not seem trivial.

00:10:55.100 --> 00:11:03.040
The proper, wise balancing of one's whole life may depend upon the feasibility of a cup of tea at an unusual hour.

00:11:04.840 --> 00:11:06.940
Signed, Arnold Bennett.

00:11:08.300 --> 00:11:09.020
End of Preface.

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:47.080
Yes, he's one of those men that don't know how to manage. Good situation, regular income,

00:11:47.440 --> 00:11:53.760
quite enough for luxuries as well as needs. Not really extravagant, and yet the fellow's

00:11:53.760 --> 00:12:00.800
always in difficulties. Somehow he gets nothing out of his money. Excellent flat, half empty,

00:12:01.220 --> 00:12:09.820
Always looks as if he'd had the brokers in. New suit, old hat. Magnificent necktie, baggy

00:12:09.820 --> 00:12:18.100
trousers. Ask you to dinner, cut glass, bad mutton. Or Turkish coffee, cracked cup.

00:12:19.240 --> 00:12:25.600
He can't understand it. Explanation simply is that he fritters his income away. Wish

00:12:25.600 --> 00:12:33.060
I had the half of it. I'd show him. So we have most of us criticised, at one time or

00:12:33.060 --> 00:12:39.600
another, in our superior way. We are nearly all chancellors of the Exchequer. It is the

00:12:39.600 --> 00:12:45.100
pride of the moment. Newspapers are full of articles explaining how to live on such and

00:12:45.100 --> 00:12:51.740
such a sum, and these articles provoke a correspondence whose violence proves the interest they excite.

00:12:52.440 --> 00:12:58.180
Recently, in a daily organ, a battle-rage drowned the question whether a woman can exist

00:12:58.180 --> 00:13:05.240
nicely in the country on eighty-five pounds a year. I have seen an essay, How to Live

00:13:05.240 --> 00:13:11.800
on Eight Shillings a Week, but I have never seen an essay, How to Live on Twenty-Four

00:13:11.800 --> 00:13:19.920
Hours a Day. Yet it has been said that time is money. That proverb understates the case.

00:13:20.600 --> 00:13:26.960
Time is a great deal more than money. If you have time, you can obtain money, usually.

00:13:27.540 --> 00:13:32.520
But though you have the wealth of a cloakroom attendant at the Carlton Hotel, you cannot

00:13:32.520 --> 00:13:37.660
buy yourself a minute more time than I have, or the cat by the fire has.

00:13:39.780 --> 00:13:46.600
Philosophers have explained space. They have not explained time. It is the inexplicable

00:13:46.600 --> 00:13:54.980
raw material of everything. With it, all is possible. Without it, nothing. The supply

00:13:54.980 --> 00:14:01.540
of time is truly a daily miracle, an affair genuinely astonishing when one examines it.

00:14:01.820 --> 00:14:07.680
You wake up in the morning, and lo! your purse is magically filled with twenty-four hours

00:14:07.680 --> 00:14:14.520
of the unmanufactured tissue of the universe of your life. It is yours. It is the most

00:14:14.520 --> 00:14:20.860
precious of possessions. A highly singular commodity showered upon you in a manner as

00:14:20.860 --> 00:14:29.340
singular as the commodity itself. For, remark, no one can take it from you. It is unstealable,

00:14:29.600 --> 00:14:36.520
and no one receives either more or less than you receive. Talk about an ideal democracy.

00:14:36.960 --> 00:14:43.040
In the realm of time there is no aristocracy of wealth and no aristocracy of intellect.

00:14:43.800 --> 00:14:51.300
Genius is never rewarded by even an extra hour a day. And there is no punishment. Waste

00:14:51.300 --> 00:14:56.940
your infinitely precious commodity as much as you will, and the supply will never be

00:14:56.940 --> 00:15:04.520
withheld from you. No mysterious power will say, This man is a fool, if not a knave. He

00:15:04.520 --> 00:15:11.480
does not deserve time. He shall be cut off at the meter. It is more certain than consoles,

00:15:11.480 --> 00:15:19.360
and payment of income is not affected by Sundays. Moreover, you cannot draw on the future. Impossible

00:15:19.360 --> 00:15:26.160
to get into debt. You can only waste the passing moment. You cannot waste tomorrow. It is kept

00:15:26.160 --> 00:15:30.660
for you. You cannot waste the next hour. It is kept for you.

00:15:31.500 --> 00:15:38.740
I said the affair was a miracle. Is it not? You have to live on this twenty-four hours

00:15:38.740 --> 00:15:46.020
of daily time. Out of it you have to spend health, pleasure, money, content, respect,

00:15:46.560 --> 00:15:53.980
and the evolution of your immortal soul. Its right use, its most effective use, is a matter

00:15:53.980 --> 00:16:02.480
of the highest urgency and of the most thrilling actuality. All depends on that. Your happiness,

00:16:02.780 --> 00:16:10.700
the elusive prize that you are all clutching for, my friends, depends on that. Strange

00:16:10.700 --> 00:16:17.880
that the newspapers, so enterprising and up-to-date as they are, are not full of how to live on

00:16:17.880 --> 00:16:24.460
a given income of time, instead of how to live on a given income of money. Money is

00:16:24.460 --> 00:16:30.640
far commoner than time. When one reflects, one perceives that money is just about the

00:16:30.640 --> 00:16:38.320
ominous thing there is. It encumbers the earth in gross heaps. If one can't contrive to live

00:16:38.320 --> 00:16:45.440
on a certain income of money, one earns a little more, or steals it, or advertises for

00:16:45.440 --> 00:16:51.260
it. One doesn't necessarily muddle one's life because one can't quite manage on a thousand

00:16:51.260 --> 00:16:57.720
pounds a year. One braces the muscles and makes it guineas and balances the budget.

00:16:57.720 --> 00:17:03.860
But if you cannot arrange that an income of twenty-four hours a day shall exactly cover

00:17:03.860 --> 00:17:10.880
all proper items of expenditure, one does muddle one's life definitely. The supply

00:17:10.880 --> 00:17:18.780
of time, though gloriously regular, is cruelly restricted. Which of us lives on twenty-four

00:17:18.780 --> 00:17:27.700
hours a day? And when I say lives, I do not mean exists, nor muddles through. What is

00:17:27.720 --> 00:17:33.020
which of us is free from that uneasy feeling that the great spending departments of his

00:17:33.020 --> 00:17:39.420
daily life are not managed as they ought to be? Which of us is quite sure that his

00:17:39.420 --> 00:17:46.180
fine suit is not surmounted by a shameful hat, or that, in attending to the crockery,

00:17:46.300 --> 00:17:53.160
he has forgotten the quality of the food? Which of us is not saying to himself, which

00:17:53.160 --> 00:17:59.320
of us has not been saying to himself all his life, I shall alter that when I have a

00:17:59.320 --> 00:18:05.920
little more time? We never shall have any more time.

00:18:06.660 --> 00:18:14.960
We have, and we have always had, all the time there is. It is the realization of this profound

00:18:14.960 --> 00:18:21.540
and neglected truth, which by the way I have not discovered, that has led me to the minute

00:18:21.540 --> 00:18:28.620
practical examination of daily time. Expenditure. End of chapter.

00:19:01.600 --> 00:19:28.620
But, someone may remark, with the English disregard of everything except the point, what is he driving at with his twenty-four hours a day? I have no difficulty in living on twenty-four hours a day. I do all that I want to do, and still find time to go in for newspaper competitions. Surely it is a simple affair, knowing that one has only twenty-four hours a day, to content oneself with twenty-four hours a day.

00:19:28.620 --> 00:19:52.560
To you, my dear sir, I present my excuses and apologies. You are precisely the man that I have been wishing to meet for about forty years. Will you kindly send me your name and address, and state your charge for telling me how you do it? Instead of me talking to you, you ought to be talking to me.

00:19:52.560 --> 00:20:22.540
That you exist, I am convinced, and that I have not yet encountered you is my loss. Meanwhile, until you appear, I will continue to chat with my companions in distress, that innumerable band of souls who are haunted, more or less painfully, by the feeling that the years slip by, and slip by, and slip by, and that they have not yet been able to get their lives into proper working conditions.

00:20:22.560 --> 00:20:51.880
If we analyse that feeling, we shall perceive it to be, primarily, one of uneasiness, of expectation, of looking forward, of aspiration. It is a source of constant discomfort, for it behaves like a skeleton at the feast of all our enjoyments. We go to the theatre and laugh, but between the acts it raises a skinny finger at us.

00:20:51.880 --> 00:21:11.120
We rush violently for the last train, and while we are cooling a long age on the platform waiting for the last train, it promenades its bones up and down by our side, and inquires, O man, what hast thou done with thy youth? What art thou doing with thine age?

00:21:11.960 --> 00:21:32.520
You may urge that this feeling of continuous looking forward, of aspiration, is part of life itself, and inseparable from life itself. True. But there are degrees. A man may desire to go to Mecca. His conscience tells him that he ought to go to Mecca.

00:21:32.520 --> 00:21:50.080
He fares forth, either by the aid of cooks, or unassisted, he may probably never reach Mecca. He may drown before he gets to Port Said. He may perish ingloriously on the coast of the Red Sea. His desire may remain eternally frustrated.

00:21:51.460 --> 00:22:04.800
Unfulfilled aspiration may always trouble him, but he will not be tormented in the same way as the man who, desiring to reach Mecca, and harried by the desire to reach Mecca, never leaves Brixton.

00:22:04.800 --> 00:22:24.080
It is something to have left Brixton. Most of us have not left Brixton. We have not even taken a cab to Luggate Circus and inquired from cooks the price of a conducted tour. And our excuse to ourselves is that there are only twenty-four hours in the day.

00:22:25.020 --> 00:22:40.940
If we further analyze our vague, uneasy aspiration, we shall, I think, see that it springs from a fixed idea that we ought to do something in addition to those things which we are loyally and morally obliged to do.

00:22:40.940 --> 00:22:57.380
We are obliged, by various codes written and unwritten, to maintain ourselves and our families, if any, in health and comfort, to pay our debts, to save, to increase our prosperity by increasing our efficiency.

00:22:57.380 --> 00:23:17.660
A task sufficiently difficult, a task which very few of us achieve, a task often beyond our skill. Yet, if we succeed in it, as we sometimes do, we are not satisfied, the skeleton is still with us.

00:23:18.340 --> 00:23:34.300
And even when we realize that the task is beyond our skill, that our powers cannot cope with it, we feel that we should be less discontented if we gave to our powers, already overtaxed, something still further to do.

00:23:34.300 --> 00:23:47.120
And such is, indeed, the fact. The wish to accomplish something outside their formal program is common to all men who in the course of evolution have risen past a certain level.

00:23:48.640 --> 00:24:02.900
Until an effort is made to satisfy that wish, the sense of uneasy waiting for something to start which has not started will remain to disturb the peace of the soul. That wish has been called by many names.

00:24:02.900 --> 00:24:21.120
It is one form of the universal desire for knowledge. And it is so strong that men whose whole lives have been given to the systematic acquirement of knowledge have been driven by it to overstep the limits of their program, in search of still more knowledge.

00:24:21.120 --> 00:24:31.840
Even Herbert Spencer, in my opinion the greatest mind that ever lived, was often forced by it into agreeable little backwaters of inquiry.

00:24:32.900 --> 00:24:47.900
I imagine that in the majority of people who are conscious of the wish to live, that is to say, people who have intellectual curiosity, the aspiration to exceed formal programs takes a literary shape.

00:24:47.900 --> 00:25:11.080
They would like to embark on a course of reading. Decidedly the British people are becoming more and more literary. But I would point out that literature by no means comprises the whole field of knowledge, and that the disturbing thirst to improve oneself, to increase one's knowledge, may well be slaked quite apart from literature.

00:25:11.780 --> 00:25:24.540
With the various ways of slaking it, I shall deal later. Here I merely point out to those who have no natural sympathy with literature, that literature is not the only well.

00:25:56.820 --> 00:26:02.980
Now that I have succeeded, if succeeded I have, in persuading you to admit to yourself

00:26:02.980 --> 00:26:08.780
that you are constantly haunted by a suppressed dissatisfaction with your own arrangement

00:26:08.780 --> 00:26:15.340
of your daily life, and that the primal cause of that inconvenient dissatisfaction is the

00:26:15.340 --> 00:26:21.420
feeling that you are, every day, leaving undone something which you would like to do, and

00:26:21.420 --> 00:26:25.880
which indeed you are always hoping to do when you have more time.

00:26:26.220 --> 00:26:30.860
And now that I have drawn your attention to the glaring, dazzling truth that you will

00:26:30.860 --> 00:26:37.740
never have more time, since you already have all the time there is, you expect me to let

00:26:37.740 --> 00:26:43.520
you into some wonderful secret by which you may at any rate approach the ideal of a perfect

00:26:43.520 --> 00:26:51.020
arrangement of the day, and by which, therefore, that haunting, unpleasant daily disappointment

00:26:51.020 --> 00:26:54.140
of things left undone will be got rid of.

00:26:55.240 --> 00:26:58.020
I have found no such wonderful secret.

00:26:58.760 --> 00:27:04.100
Nor do I expect to find it, nor do I expect that anyone else will ever find it.

00:27:04.420 --> 00:27:05.880
It is undiscovered.

00:27:06.380 --> 00:27:11.980
When you first began to gather my drift, perhaps there was a resurrection of hope in your breast.

00:27:12.540 --> 00:27:18.800
Perhaps you said to yourself, This man will show me an easy, unfatiguing way of doing

00:27:18.800 --> 00:27:21.420
what I have so long in vain wished to do.

00:27:22.040 --> 00:27:23.100
Alas, no!

00:27:23.380 --> 00:27:27.920
The fact is that there is no easy way, no royal road.

00:27:28.400 --> 00:27:34.880
The path to Mecca is extremely hard and stony, and the worst of it is that you never quite

00:27:34.880 --> 00:27:36.420
get there, after all.

00:27:37.500 --> 00:27:42.500
The most important preliminary to the task of arranging one's life so that one may live

00:27:42.500 --> 00:27:48.740
Fully and comfortably within one's daily budget of twenty-four hours is the calm realization

00:27:48.740 --> 00:27:54.860
of the extreme difficulty of the task, of the sacrifices and the endless effort which

00:27:54.860 --> 00:27:55.660
it demands.

00:27:56.120 --> 00:27:58.780
I cannot too strongly insist on this.

00:27:59.900 --> 00:28:06.080
If you imagine that you will be able to achieve your ideal by ingeniously planning out a timetable

00:28:06.080 --> 00:28:10.680
with a pen on a piece of paper, you had better give up hope at once.

00:28:11.380 --> 00:28:16.640
If you are not prepared for discouragements and dissolutions, if you will not be content

00:28:16.640 --> 00:28:23.860
with a small result for a big effort, then do not begin, lie down again, and resume the

00:28:23.860 --> 00:28:26.760
uneasy doze which you call your existence.

00:28:28.100 --> 00:28:32.760
It is very sad, is it not, very depressing and sombre?

00:28:33.060 --> 00:28:38.640
And yet I think it is rather fine, too, this necessity for the tense bracing of the will

00:28:38.640 --> 00:28:41.000
before anything worth doing can be done.

00:28:41.600 --> 00:28:43.640
I rather like it myself.

00:28:44.040 --> 00:28:48.740
I feel it to be the chief thing that differentiates me from the cat by the fire.

00:28:49.820 --> 00:28:56.320
Well, you say, assume that I embraced for the battle, assume that I have carefully weighed

00:28:56.320 --> 00:28:58.780
and comprehended your ponderous remarks.

00:28:59.200 --> 00:29:00.860
How do I begin?

00:29:02.060 --> 00:29:04.720
Dear sir, you simply begin.

00:29:05.200 --> 00:29:07.620
There is no magic method of beginning.

00:29:08.160 --> 00:29:12.980
If a man standing on the edge of a swimming-bath and wanting to jump into the cold water should

00:29:12.980 --> 00:29:15.560
ask you, How do I begin to jump?

00:29:16.080 --> 00:29:21.740
You would merely reply, Just jump, take hold of your nerves and jump.

00:29:22.920 --> 00:29:28.240
As I have previously said, the chief beauty about the constant supply of time is that

00:29:28.240 --> 00:29:30.500
you cannot waste it in advance.

00:29:31.020 --> 00:29:39.180
The next year, the next day, the next hour are lying ready for you, as perfect, as unspoilt,

00:29:39.660 --> 00:29:44.280
as if you had never wasted or misapplied a single moment in all your career.

00:29:45.100 --> 00:29:48.220
Which fact is very gratifying and reassuring.

00:29:48.660 --> 00:29:51.840
You can turn over a new leaf every hour if you choose.

00:29:52.560 --> 00:29:57.180
Therefore, no object is served in waiting till next week or even until tomorrow.

00:29:57.620 --> 00:30:00.900
You may fancy that the water will be warmer next week.

00:30:01.320 --> 00:30:02.160
It won't.

00:30:02.260 --> 00:30:03.220
It will be colder.

00:30:04.460 --> 00:30:10.760
But before you begin, let me murmur a few words of warning in your private ear.

00:30:12.080 --> 00:30:15.540
Let me principally warn you against your own ardour.

00:30:16.320 --> 00:30:20.460
Ardour in well-doing is a misleading and a treacherous thing.

00:30:21.180 --> 00:30:23.460
It cries out loudly for employment.

00:30:24.200 --> 00:30:26.400
You can't satisfy it at first.

00:30:26.400 --> 00:30:28.520
It wants more and more.

00:30:28.740 --> 00:30:32.680
It is eager to move mountains and divert the course of rivers.

00:30:33.560 --> 00:30:36.200
It isn't content till it perspires.

00:30:36.320 --> 00:30:43.000
And then, too often, when it feels the perspiration on its brow, it wearies all of a sudden and

00:30:43.000 --> 00:30:48.920
dies, without even putting itself to the trouble of saying, I've had enough of this.

00:30:50.260 --> 00:30:52.980
Beware of undertaking too much at the start.

00:30:53.540 --> 00:30:55.480
Be content with quite a little.

00:30:55.480 --> 00:30:57.400
Allow for accidents.

00:30:58.080 --> 00:31:01.700
Allow for human nature, especially your own.

00:31:02.580 --> 00:31:08.860
A failure or so in itself would not matter if it did not incur a loss of self-esteem

00:31:08.860 --> 00:31:10.180
and of self-confidence.

00:31:10.900 --> 00:31:16.700
But just as nothing succeeds like success, so nothing fails like failure.

00:31:17.560 --> 00:31:21.740
Most people who are ruined are ruined by attempting too much.

00:31:21.740 --> 00:31:27.440
Therefore, in setting out on the immense enterprise of living fully and comfortably

00:31:27.440 --> 00:31:33.620
within the narrow limits of twenty-four hours a day, let us avoid at any cost the risk of

00:31:33.620 --> 00:31:34.600
an early failure.

00:31:35.140 --> 00:31:41.220
I will not agree that, in this business at any rate, a glorious failure is better than

00:31:41.220 --> 00:31:42.460
a petty success.

00:31:42.820 --> 00:31:45.700
I am all for the petty success.

00:31:46.160 --> 00:31:48.300
A glorious failure leads to nothing.

00:31:48.300 --> 00:31:52.440
A petty success may lead to a success that is not petty.

00:31:53.400 --> 00:31:56.820
So let us begin to examine the budget of the day's time.

00:31:57.600 --> 00:32:00.360
You say your day is already full to overflowing.

00:32:00.960 --> 00:32:01.560
How?

00:32:02.100 --> 00:32:05.840
You actually spend in earning your livelihood how much?

00:32:06.400 --> 00:32:08.080
Seven hours on the average?

00:32:08.600 --> 00:32:09.820
And an actual sleep?

00:32:10.300 --> 00:32:10.720
Seven?

00:32:11.460 --> 00:32:13.960
I will add two hours and be generous.

00:32:13.960 --> 00:32:19.660
And I will defy you to account me on the spur of the moment for the other eight hours.

00:32:48.040 --> 00:32:52.240
IV. The Cause of the Troubles

00:32:53.400 --> 00:32:58.620
In order to come to grips at once with the question of time expenditure in all

00:32:58.620 --> 00:33:04.380
its actuality, I must choose an individual case for examination. I can

00:33:04.380 --> 00:33:09.880
only deal with one case, and that case cannot be the average case, because there

00:33:09.880 --> 00:33:16.200
is no such case as the average case, just as there is no such man as the average

00:33:16.200 --> 00:33:22.980
man. Every man and every man's case is special. But if I take the case of a

00:33:22.980 --> 00:33:28.500
Londoner who works in an office whose office hours are from 10 to 6, and who

00:33:28.500 --> 00:33:33.040
spends 50 minutes morning and night in traveling between his house door and his

00:33:33.040 --> 00:33:38.660
office door, I shall have got as near to the average as facts permit. There are

00:33:38.660 --> 00:33:43.000
men who have to work longer for a living, but there are others who do not have to

00:33:43.000 --> 00:33:48.700
work so long. Fortunately, the financial side of existence does not interest us

00:33:48.700 --> 00:33:54.460
here. For our present purpose, the clerk at a pound a week is exactly as well off

00:33:54.460 --> 00:33:59.660
as the millionaire in Carlton House Terrace. Now the great and profound

00:33:59.660 --> 00:34:05.340
mistake which my typical man makes in regard to his day is a mistake of general

00:34:05.340 --> 00:34:10.860
attitude, a mistake which vitiates and weakens two-thirds of his energies and

00:34:10.860 --> 00:34:17.760
interests. In the majority of instances, he does not precisely feel a passion for

00:34:17.760 --> 00:34:23.400
his business. At best, he does not dislike it. He begins his business

00:34:23.400 --> 00:34:29.900
functions with reluctance, as late as he can, and he ends them with joy, as early

00:34:29.900 --> 00:34:34.740
as he can, and his engines while he is engaged in his business are seldom at

00:34:34.740 --> 00:34:40.420
their full horsepower. I know that I shall be accused by angry readers of

00:34:40.420 --> 00:34:44.800
traducing the city worker, but I am pretty thoroughly acquainted with the

00:34:44.800 --> 00:34:51.340
city, and I stick to what I say. Yet in spite of all this, he persists in

00:34:51.340 --> 00:34:57.280
looking upon those hours from ten to six as the day, to which the ten hours

00:34:57.280 --> 00:35:02.060
preceding them and the six hours following them are nothing but a prologue

00:35:02.060 --> 00:35:08.200
and epilogue. Such an attitude, unconscious though it be, of course kills

00:35:08.200 --> 00:35:13.240
his interest in the odd sixteen hours, with the result that, even if he does

00:35:13.240 --> 00:35:19.840
not waste them, he does not count them, he regards them simply as margin. This

00:35:19.840 --> 00:35:25.300
general attitude is utterly illogical and unhealthy, since it formally gives

00:35:25.300 --> 00:35:30.300
the central prominence to a patch of time and a bunch of activities which

00:35:30.300 --> 00:35:36.140
the man's one idea is to get through and have done with. If a man makes two-

00:35:36.140 --> 00:35:41.100
thirds of his existence subservient to one-third, for which admittedly he has

00:35:41.100 --> 00:35:47.820
no absolutely feverish zest, how can he hope to live fully and completely? He

00:35:47.820 --> 00:35:53.920
cannot. If my typical man wishes to live fully and completely, he must, in his

00:35:53.920 --> 00:36:01.120
mind, arrange a day within a day. And this inner day, a Chinese box in a larger

00:36:01.120 --> 00:36:09.040
Chinese box, must begin at six p.m. and end at ten a.m. It is a day of sixteen

00:36:09.040 --> 00:36:14.620
hours, and during all these sixteen hours he has nothing whatever to do but

00:36:14.620 --> 00:36:20.640
cultivate his body and his soul and his fellow men. During those sixteen hours he

00:36:20.640 --> 00:36:27.780
is free. He is not a wage earner, he is not preoccupied with monetary cares, he

00:36:27.780 --> 00:36:34.120
is just as good as a man with a private income. This must be his attitude, and his

00:36:34.120 --> 00:36:40.580
attitude is all-important. His success in life, much more important than the amount

00:36:40.580 --> 00:36:46.500
of estate upon which his executors will have to pay estate duty, depends on it.

00:36:46.860 --> 00:36:52.260
What? You say that full energy given to those sixteen hours will lessen the

00:36:53.040 --> 00:37:00.420
eight? Not so. On the contrary, it will assuredly increase the value of the

00:37:00.420 --> 00:37:05.780
business eight. One of the chief things which my typical man has to learn is

00:37:05.780 --> 00:37:11.560
that the mental faculties are capable of a continuous hard activity. They do not

00:37:11.560 --> 00:37:19.640
tire like an arm or a leg. All they want is change, not rest, except in sleep. I

00:37:19.640 --> 00:37:23.760
shall now examine the typical man's current method of employing the sixteen

00:37:23.760 --> 00:37:29.380
hours that are entirely his, beginning with his uprising. I will merely

00:37:29.380 --> 00:37:34.340
indicate things which he does and which I think he ought not to do, postponing

00:37:34.340 --> 00:37:39.760
my suggestions for planting the times when I shall have cleared, as a settler

00:37:39.760 --> 00:37:45.760
clears spaces in a forest. Injustice to him, I must say, that he wastes very

00:37:45.760 --> 00:37:51.160
little time before he leaves the house in the morning at nine-ten. In too many

00:37:51.160 --> 00:37:56.980
houses he gets up at nine, breakfasts between nine-seven and nine-nine-and-a-

00:37:56.980 --> 00:38:01.760
half, and then bolts. But immediately he bangs the front door, his mental

00:38:01.760 --> 00:38:07.860
faculties, which are tireless, become idle. He walks to the station in a

00:38:07.860 --> 00:38:14.380
condition of mental coma. Arrived there, he usually has to wait for the train. On

00:38:14.380 --> 00:38:19.720
hundreds of suburban stations every morning you see men calmly strolling up

00:38:19.720 --> 00:38:24.960
and down platforms, while railway companies unblushingly rob them of time,

00:38:25.320 --> 00:38:30.940
which is more than money. Hundreds of thousands of hours are thus lost every

00:38:30.940 --> 00:38:36.260
day simply because my typical man thinks so little of time that it has never

00:38:36.260 --> 00:38:41.200
occurred to him to take quite easy precautions against the risk of its loss.

00:38:41.760 --> 00:38:49.540
He has a solid coin of time to spend every day. Call it a sovereign. He must

00:38:49.540 --> 00:38:54.320
get change for it, and in getting change he is content to lose heavily.

00:38:55.880 --> 00:39:01.000
Supposing that in selling him a ticket, the company said, We will change your

00:39:01.000 --> 00:39:10.020
sovereign, but we shall charge you three halfpence for doing so. What would my

00:39:10.020 --> 00:39:14.880
equivalent of what the company does when it robs him of five minutes twice a day?

00:39:16.000 --> 00:39:23.840
You say I am dealing with minutiae. I am, and later on I will justify myself. Now

00:39:23.840 --> 00:39:29.680
will you kindly buy your paper and step onto the train? End of chapter.

00:40:02.560 --> 00:40:30.520
You get into the morning train with your newspaper, and you calmly and majestically give yourself up to your newspaper. You do not hurry. You know you have at least half an hour of security in front of you. As your glance lingers idly at the advertisements of shipping and of songs on the outer pages, your air is the air of a leisured man, wealthy in time, of a man from some planet where there are

00:40:30.520 --> 00:40:58.240
a hundred and twenty-four hours a day, instead of twenty-four. I am an impassioned reader of newspapers. I read five English and two French dailies, and the newsagents alone know how many weeklies, regularly. I am obliged to mention this personal fact, lest I should be accused of a prejudice against newspapers, when I say that I object to the reading of newspapers in the morning train.

00:40:59.320 --> 00:41:28.220
Newspapers are produced with rapidity, to be read with rapidity. There is no place in my daily program for newspapers. I read them, as I may, in odd moments, but I do read them, the idea of devoting to them thirty or forty consecutive minutes of wonderful solitude, for nowhere can one more perfectly immerse oneself in oneself than in a compartment full of silent, withdrawn, smothered, and empty.

00:41:28.240 --> 00:41:55.380
I cannot possibly allow you to scatter priceless pearls of time with such oriental lavishness. You are not the shah of time. Let me respectfully remind you that you have no more time than I have, no newspaper reading in trains. I have already put by about three-quarters of an hour for use.

00:41:56.580 --> 00:42:01.280
Now you reach your office, and I abandon you there till six o'clock.

00:42:01.840 --> 00:42:08.140
I am aware that you have nominally an hour, often in reality an hour and a half, in the

00:42:08.140 --> 00:42:11.960
midst of the day, less than half of which time is given to eating.

00:42:12.680 --> 00:42:15.880
But I will leave you all that to spend as you choose.

00:42:16.120 --> 00:42:18.100
You may read your newspapers then.

00:42:19.140 --> 00:42:22.260
I meet you again as you emerge from your office.

00:42:22.600 --> 00:42:24.320
You are pale and tired.

00:42:24.840 --> 00:42:30.220
At any rate, your wife says you are pale and you give her to understand that you are tired.

00:42:31.420 --> 00:42:36.540
During the journey home, you have been gradually working up the tired feeling.

00:42:37.280 --> 00:42:43.460
The tired feeling hangs heavy over the mighty suburbs of London like a virtuous and melancholy

00:42:43.460 --> 00:42:45.920
cloud, particularly in winter.

00:42:46.640 --> 00:42:52.440
You don't eat immediately on your arrival home, but in about an hour or so you feel

00:42:52.440 --> 00:42:55.900
as if you could sit up and take a little nourishment.

00:42:56.320 --> 00:42:57.320
And you do.

00:42:57.920 --> 00:42:59.880
Then you smoke seriously.

00:43:00.480 --> 00:43:01.440
You see friends.

00:43:01.960 --> 00:43:02.780
You potter.

00:43:03.200 --> 00:43:04.320
You play cards.

00:43:04.640 --> 00:43:05.800
You flirt with a book.

00:43:06.460 --> 00:43:08.920
You note that old age is creeping on.

00:43:09.400 --> 00:43:10.660
You take a stroll.

00:43:11.000 --> 00:43:12.480
You caress the piano.

00:43:13.000 --> 00:43:15.600
By Jove, a quarter past eleven.

00:43:16.420 --> 00:43:20.400
You then devote quite forty minutes to thinking about going to bed.

00:43:20.640 --> 00:43:24.780
And it is conceivable that you are acquainted with a genuinely good whiskey.

00:43:25.840 --> 00:43:29.580
At last you go to bed, exhausted by the day's work.

00:43:30.080 --> 00:43:34.660
Six hours, probably more, have gone since you left the office.

00:43:34.980 --> 00:43:36.300
Gone like a dream.

00:43:36.840 --> 00:43:38.220
Gone like magic.

00:43:39.020 --> 00:43:40.380
Unaccountably gone.

00:43:42.180 --> 00:43:44.280
That is a fair sample case.

00:43:44.660 --> 00:43:48.780
But you say it's all very well for you to talk.

00:43:48.780 --> 00:43:50.860
A man is tired.

00:43:51.200 --> 00:43:53.040
A man must see his friends.

00:43:53.440 --> 00:43:55.600
He can't always be on the stretch.

00:43:56.620 --> 00:43:57.660
Just so.

00:43:58.040 --> 00:44:03.800
But when you arrange to go to the theatre, especially with a pretty woman, what happens?

00:44:04.260 --> 00:44:05.760
You rush to the suburbs.

00:44:06.160 --> 00:44:09.840
You spare no toil to make yourself glorious and fine raiment.

00:44:10.460 --> 00:44:12.660
You rush back to town in another train.

00:44:13.180 --> 00:44:17.180
You keep yourself on the stretch for four hours, if not five.

00:44:17.600 --> 00:44:18.940
You take her home.

00:44:19.340 --> 00:44:20.660
You take yourself home.

00:44:21.160 --> 00:44:25.020
You don't spend three-quarters of an hour in thinking about going to bed.

00:44:25.520 --> 00:44:26.340
You go.

00:44:26.980 --> 00:44:29.820
Friends and fatigue have equally been forgotten.

00:44:30.200 --> 00:44:33.460
And the evening has seemed so exquisitely long.

00:44:33.900 --> 00:44:35.600
Or perhaps too short.

00:44:36.660 --> 00:44:41.420
And do you remember that time when you were persuaded to sing in the chorus of the Amateur

00:44:41.420 --> 00:44:46.760
Operatic Society and slaved two hours every other night for three months?

00:44:47.620 --> 00:44:52.460
Can you deny that when you have something definite to look forward to at even tide,

00:44:52.940 --> 00:44:58.460
something that is to employ all your energy, the thought of that something gives a glow

00:44:58.460 --> 00:45:01.960
and a more intense vitality to the whole day?

00:45:03.380 --> 00:45:09.880
What I suggest is that at six o'clock you look facts in the face and admit that you are not

00:45:09.880 --> 00:45:15.840
tired, because you are not, you know, and that you arrange your evening so that it is

00:45:15.840 --> 00:45:17.840
not cut in the middle by a meal.

00:45:18.520 --> 00:45:23.020
By so doing you will have a clear expanse of at least three hours.

00:45:23.540 --> 00:45:28.780
I do not suggest that you should employ three hours every night of your life in using up

00:45:28.780 --> 00:45:29.920
your mental energy.

00:45:30.600 --> 00:45:37.720
But I do suggest that you might, for commencement, employ an hour and a half every other evening

00:45:37.720 --> 00:45:41.480
in some important and consecutive cultivation of the mind.

00:45:42.400 --> 00:45:48.000
You will still be left with three evenings for friends, bridge, tennis, domestic scenes,

00:45:48.520 --> 00:45:53.960
odd reading, pipes, gardening, pottering, and prize competitions.

00:45:54.480 --> 00:46:00.820
You will still have the terrific wealth of 45 hours between 2 p.m. Saturday and 10 a.m.

00:46:00.820 --> 00:46:01.360
Monday.

00:46:02.300 --> 00:46:09.500
If you persevere, you will soon want to pass four evenings, and perhaps five, in some sustained

00:46:09.500 --> 00:46:15.380
endeavor to be genuinely alive, and you will fall out of that habit of muttering to yourself

00:46:15.380 --> 00:46:17.240
at 11.15 p.m.

00:46:17.740 --> 00:46:20.360
Time to be thinking about going to bed.

00:46:21.360 --> 00:46:27.140
The man who begins to go to bed 40 minutes before he opens his bedroom door is bored.

00:46:27.680 --> 00:46:30.380
That is to say, he is not living.

00:46:31.760 --> 00:46:39.120
But remember, at the start, those 90 nocturnal minutes, thrice a week, must be the most important

00:46:39.120 --> 00:46:41.260
minutes in the 10,080.

00:46:41.940 --> 00:46:47.360
They must be sacred, quite as sacred as a dramatic rehearsal or a tennis match.

00:46:48.120 --> 00:46:53.900
Instead of saying, sorry, I can't see you, old chap, but I have to run off to the tennis

00:46:53.900 --> 00:46:54.280
club.

00:46:54.740 --> 00:46:57.920
You must say, but I have to work.

00:46:58.780 --> 00:47:01.780
This I admit is intensely difficult to say.

00:47:02.360 --> 00:47:06.040
Tennis is so much more urgent than the immortal soul.

00:47:33.960 --> 00:47:35.800
Remember Human Nature.

00:47:38.460 --> 00:47:43.580
I have incidentally mentioned the vast expanse of forty-five hours between leaving business

00:47:43.580 --> 00:47:48.820
at two p.m. on Saturday and returning to business at ten a.m. on Monday.

00:47:49.900 --> 00:47:54.720
And here I must touch on the point whether the week should consist of six days or of

00:47:54.720 --> 00:47:55.000
seven.

00:47:55.620 --> 00:48:03.160
For many years, in fact, until I was approaching forty, my own week consisted of seven days.

00:48:03.540 --> 00:48:09.840
I was constantly being informed by older and wiser people that more work, more genuine

00:48:09.840 --> 00:48:13.620
living could be got out of six days than out of seven.

00:48:15.140 --> 00:48:20.300
And it is certainly true that now, with one day in seven in which I follow no program

00:48:20.300 --> 00:48:27.100
and make no effort save what the caprice of the moment dictates, I appreciate intensely

00:48:27.100 --> 00:48:29.520
the moral value of a weekly rest.

00:48:30.460 --> 00:48:36.400
Nevertheless, had I my life to arrange over again, I would do again as I have done.

00:48:37.000 --> 00:48:43.420
Only those who have lived at the full stretch seven days a week for a long time can appreciate

00:48:43.420 --> 00:48:46.640
the full beauty of a regular recurring idleness.

00:48:47.740 --> 00:48:51.960
Moreover I am aging, and it is a question of age.

00:48:52.640 --> 00:48:58.480
In cases of abounding youth and exceptional energy and desire for effort, I should say

00:48:59.280 --> 00:49:02.680
unhesitatingly, keep going day in, day out.

00:49:03.500 --> 00:49:10.440
But in the average case I should say, confine your formal program, super program I mean,

00:49:10.860 --> 00:49:12.240
to six days a week.

00:49:12.840 --> 00:49:18.800
If you find yourself wishing to extend it, extend it, but only in proportion to your

00:49:18.800 --> 00:49:26.220
wish, and count the extra time as a windfall, not as regular income, so that you can return

00:49:26.220 --> 00:49:32.860
to a six-day program without the sensation of being poorer, of being a backslider.

00:49:33.940 --> 00:49:35.860
Let us now see where we stand.

00:49:36.360 --> 00:49:42.560
So far we have marked for saving out of the waste of days half an hour at least on six

00:49:42.560 --> 00:49:49.260
mornings a week, and one hour and a half on three evenings a week, total seven hours and

00:49:49.260 --> 00:49:50.180
a half a week.

00:49:51.060 --> 00:49:55.820
I propose to be content with that seven hours and a half for the present.

00:49:56.660 --> 00:50:03.600
What, you cry, you pretend to show us how to live, and you only deal with seven hours

00:50:03.600 --> 00:50:05.900
and a half out of a hundred and sixty-eight?

00:50:06.520 --> 00:50:10.180
Are you going to perform a miracle with your seven hours and a half?

00:50:11.220 --> 00:50:17.140
Well, not to mince the matter, I am, if you will kindly let me.

00:50:17.140 --> 00:50:23.800
That is to say, I am going to ask you to attempt an experience which, while perfectly natural

00:50:23.800 --> 00:50:27.600
and explicable, has all the air of a miracle.

00:50:28.500 --> 00:50:33.820
My contention is that the full use of those seven and one-half hours will quicken the

00:50:33.820 --> 00:50:39.640
whole life of the week, add zest to it, and increase the interest which you feel in even

00:50:39.640 --> 00:50:41.820
the most banal occupations.

00:50:42.500 --> 00:50:48.460
You practice physical exercises for a mere ten minutes morning and evening, and yet you

00:50:48.460 --> 00:50:53.440
are not astonished when your physical health and strength are beneficially affected every

00:50:53.440 --> 00:50:57.440
hour of the day, and your whole physical outlook changed.

00:50:58.200 --> 00:51:04.000
Why should you be astonished that an average of over an hour a day given to the mind should

00:51:04.000 --> 00:51:07.960
permanently and completely enliven the whole activity of the mind?

00:51:09.040 --> 00:51:15.140
More time might assuredly be given to the cultivation of oneself, and in proportion

00:51:15.140 --> 00:51:17.960
as the time was longer the results would be greater.

00:51:18.880 --> 00:51:22.420
But I prefer to begin with what looks like a trifling effort.

00:51:23.540 --> 00:51:29.740
It is not really a trifling effort, as those will discover who have yet to assay it.

00:51:30.140 --> 00:51:36.700
To clear even seven hours and a half from the jungle is passably difficult, for some

00:51:36.700 --> 00:51:38.860
sacrifice has to be made.

00:51:39.280 --> 00:51:44.020
One may have spent one's time badly, but one did spend it.

00:51:44.340 --> 00:51:48.980
One did do something with it, however ill-advised that something may have been.

00:51:49.600 --> 00:51:52.780
To do something else means a change of habits.

00:51:53.640 --> 00:51:56.720
And habits are the very dickens to change.

00:51:57.640 --> 00:52:03.880
Further, any change, even a change for the better, is always accompanied by drawbacks

00:52:03.880 --> 00:52:05.440
and discomforts.

00:52:05.440 --> 00:52:11.440
If you imagine that you will be able to devote seven hours and a half a week to serious continuous

00:52:11.440 --> 00:52:16.980
effort, and still live your old life, you are mistaken.

00:52:17.700 --> 00:52:24.740
I repeat that some sacrifice, and an immense deal of volition, will be necessary.

00:52:25.360 --> 00:52:31.380
And it is because I know the difficulty, it is because I know the almost disastrous effect

00:52:31.380 --> 00:52:37.340
in such an enterprise that I earnestly advise a very humble beginning.

00:52:38.020 --> 00:52:40.960
You must safeguard your self-respect.

00:52:41.820 --> 00:52:47.720
Self-respect is at the root of all purposefulness, and a failure in an enterprise deliberately

00:52:47.720 --> 00:52:52.040
planned deals a desperate wound at one's self-respect.

00:52:52.960 --> 00:52:59.380
Hence I iterate and reiterate, start quietly, unostentatiously.

00:53:00.320 --> 00:53:05.080
When you have conscientiously given seven hours and a half a week to the cultivation

00:53:05.080 --> 00:53:11.480
of your vitality for three months, then you may begin to sing louder and tell yourself

00:53:11.480 --> 00:53:14.180
what wondrous things you are capable of doing.

00:53:15.280 --> 00:53:21.620
Before coming to the method of using the indicated hours, I have one final suggestion to make.

00:53:21.880 --> 00:53:28.240
That is, as regards the evenings, to allow much more than an hour and a half in which

00:53:28.240 --> 00:53:30.960
to do the work of an hour and a half.

00:53:31.380 --> 00:53:33.080
Remember the chance of accidents.

00:53:33.900 --> 00:53:35.420
Remember human nature.

00:53:36.040 --> 00:53:42.280
And give yourself, say, from nine to eleven thirty for your task of ninety minutes.

00:54:14.260 --> 00:54:15.780
CONTROLING THE MIND.

00:54:19.040 --> 00:54:26.520
People say, one can't help one's thoughts, but one can. The control of the thinking machine

00:54:26.520 --> 00:54:32.500
is perfectly possible, and since nothing whatever happens to us outside our own brain,

00:54:32.1000 --> 00:54:37.100
since nothing hurts us or gives us pleasure except within the brain,

00:54:37.780 --> 00:54:42.760
the supreme importance of being able to control what goes on in that mysterious brain

00:54:42.760 --> 00:54:50.220
is patent. This idea is one of the oldest platitudes, but it is a platitude whose profound

00:54:50.220 --> 00:54:58.140
truth and urgency most people live and die without realizing. People complain of the lack of power to

00:54:58.140 --> 00:55:05.500
concentrate, not witting that they may acquire the power if they choose. And without the power to

00:55:05.500 --> 00:55:12.660
concentrate, that is to say, without the power to dictate to the brain its task and to ensure

00:55:12.660 --> 00:55:19.760
obedience, true life is impossible. Mind control is the first element of a full existence.

00:55:20.920 --> 00:55:27.040
Hence, it seems to me, the first business of the day should be to put the mind through its paces.

00:55:27.480 --> 00:55:33.880
You look after your body, inside and out. You run grave danger in hacking hairs off your skin.

00:55:34.380 --> 00:55:38.920
You employ a whole army of individuals, from the milkman to the pig killer,

00:55:38.920 --> 00:55:45.920
to enable you to bribe your stomach into decent behavior. Why not devote a little attention to

00:55:45.920 --> 00:55:52.940
the far more delicate machinery of the mind, especially as you will require no extraneous aid?

00:55:53.780 --> 00:55:58.800
It is for this portion of the art and craft of living that I have reserved the time,

00:55:59.180 --> 00:56:03.220
from the moment of quitting your door to the moment of arriving at your office.

00:56:04.180 --> 00:56:11.360
What, I am to cultivate my mind in the street, on the platform, in the train,

00:56:11.700 --> 00:56:18.780
and in the crowded street again? Precisely, nothing simpler, no tools required,

00:56:18.1000 --> 00:56:26.520
not even a book. Nevertheless, the affair is not easy. When you leave your house,

00:56:26.520 --> 00:56:32.920
concentrate your mind on a subject, no matter what, to begin with. You will not have gone

00:56:32.920 --> 00:56:38.580
ten yards before your mind has skipped away under your very eyes and is lurking around the corner

00:56:38.580 --> 00:56:45.320
with another subject. Bring it back by the scruff of the neck. Ere you have reached the station,

00:56:45.440 --> 00:56:52.720
you will have brought it back about forty times. To not despair, continue, keep it up. You will

00:56:52.720 --> 00:57:00.040
succeed. You cannot by any chance fail if you persevere. It is idle to pretend that your mind

00:57:00.040 --> 00:57:06.540
is incapable of concentration. Do you not remember that morning when you received a disquieting

00:57:06.540 --> 00:57:13.180
letter which demanded a very carefully worded answer? How you kept your mind steadily on the

00:57:13.180 --> 00:57:18.360
subject of the answer, without a second's intermission, until you reached your office?

00:57:18.360 --> 00:57:22.040
Whereupon you instantly sat down and wrote the answer.

00:57:22.940 --> 00:57:29.460
That was a case in which you were aroused by circumstances to such a degree of vitality

00:57:29.460 --> 00:57:36.840
that you were able to dominate your mind like a tyrant. You would have no trifling. You insisted

00:57:36.840 --> 00:57:44.580
that its work should be done, and its work was done. By the regular practice of concentration,

00:57:44.580 --> 00:57:51.700
as to which there is no secret, save the secret of perseverance, you can tyrannize over your mind,

00:57:52.120 --> 00:57:58.500
which is not the highest part of you, every hour of the day, and in no matter what place.

00:57:59.140 --> 00:58:05.780
The exercise is a very convenient one. If you got into your morning train with a pair of dumbbells

00:58:05.780 --> 00:58:12.020
for your muscles, or an encyclopedia in ten volumes for your learning, you would probably

00:58:12.020 --> 00:58:18.620
excite remark. But as you walk in the street, or sit in the corner of the compartment behind a pipe,

00:58:19.220 --> 00:58:25.280
or strap hang on the subterranean, who is to know that you are engaged in the most important

00:58:25.280 --> 00:58:33.100
of daily acts? What asinine boer can laugh at you? I do not care what you concentrate on,

00:58:33.260 --> 00:58:39.540
so long as you concentrate. It is the mere disciplining of the thinking machine that counts.

00:58:40.180 --> 00:58:46.340
But still, you may as well kill two birds with one stone, and concentrate on something useful.

00:58:47.020 --> 00:58:53.340
I suggest, it is only a suggestion, a little chapter of Marcus Aurelius or Epictetus.

00:58:54.480 --> 00:59:00.680
Do not, I beg, shy at their names. For myself, I know nothing more actual,

00:59:01.160 --> 00:59:07.840
more bursting with plain common sense applicable to the daily life of plain persons like you and me,

00:59:07.840 --> 00:59:13.820
who hate errors, pose and nonsense, than Marcus Aurelius or Epictetus.

00:59:14.540 --> 00:59:19.520
Read a chapter, and so short they are the chapters, in the evening,

00:59:19.840 --> 00:59:23.180
and concentrated on it the next morning. You will see.

00:59:24.020 --> 00:59:30.220
Yes, my friend, it is useless for you to try to disguise the fact. I can hear your

00:59:30.220 --> 00:59:34.400
brain like a telephone at my ear. You are saying to yourself,

00:59:34.960 --> 00:59:40.580
This fellow was doing pretty well up to his seventh chapter. He had begun to interest

00:59:40.580 --> 00:59:46.840
me faintly. But what he says about thinking in trains, and concentration, and so on,

00:59:46.840 --> 00:59:52.380
is not for me. It may be well enough for some folks, but it isn't in my line.

00:59:53.560 --> 01:00:03.140
It is for you, I passionately repeat. It is for you. Indeed, you are the very man I am aiming at.

01:00:04.020 --> 01:00:10.420
Throw away the suggestion, and you throw away the most precious suggestion that was ever offered to

01:00:10.420 --> 01:00:17.660
you. It is not my suggestion. It is the suggestion of the most sensible, practical, hard-headed men

01:00:17.660 --> 01:00:24.860
who have walked the earth. I only give it to you at second hand. Try it. Get your mind in hand,

01:00:25.380 --> 01:00:32.340
and see how the process cures half the evils of life, especially worry, that miserable,

01:00:32.340 --> 01:00:38.640
avoidable, shameful disease, worry. End of chapter.

01:01:07.200 --> 01:01:14.400
THE REFLECTIVE MOOD. The exercise of concentrating the mind, to which at

01:01:14.400 --> 01:01:20.300
least half an hour a day should be given, is a mere preliminary, like scales on the

01:01:20.300 --> 01:01:25.860
piano. Having acquired power over that most unruly member of one's complex

01:01:25.860 --> 01:01:31.780
organism, one is naturally to put it to the yoke. Useless to possess an obedient

01:01:31.780 --> 01:01:37.580
mind, unless one profits to the furthest possible degree by its obedience. A

01:01:37.580 --> 01:01:43.440
prolonged primary course of study is indicated. Now as to what this course of

01:01:43.440 --> 01:01:49.340
study should be, cannot be any question. There never has been any question. All

01:01:49.340 --> 01:01:54.420
the sensible people of all ages are agreed upon it, and it is not literature,

01:01:54.840 --> 01:02:01.620
nor is it any other art, nor is it history, nor is it any science. It is the

01:02:01.620 --> 01:02:09.880
study of one's self. Man, know thyself. These words are so hackneyed that

01:02:09.880 --> 01:02:15.120
verily I blush to write them. Yet they must be written, for they need to be

01:02:15.120 --> 01:02:22.820
written. I take back my blush, being ashamed of it. Man, know thyself. I say it

01:02:22.820 --> 01:02:27.620
out loud. The phrase is one of those phrases with which everyone is familiar,

01:02:27.620 --> 01:02:33.100
of which everyone acknowledges the value, and which only the most sagacious put

01:02:33.100 --> 01:02:38.820
into practice. I don't know why. I am entirely convinced that what is more

01:02:38.820 --> 01:02:43.960
than anything else lacking in the life of the averaged well-intentioned man of

01:02:43.960 --> 01:02:51.420
today is the reflective mood. We do not reflect. I mean that we do not reflect

01:02:51.420 --> 01:02:57.020
upon genuinely important things, upon the problem of our happiness, upon the

01:02:57.020 --> 01:03:02.880
main direction in which we are going, upon what life is giving to us, upon the

01:03:02.880 --> 01:03:09.020
share which reason has, or has not, in determining our actions, and upon the

01:03:09.020 --> 01:03:14.420
relation between our principles and our conduct. And yet you are in search of

01:03:14.420 --> 01:03:20.840
happiness, are you not? Have you discovered it? The chances are that you

01:03:20.840 --> 01:03:25.280
have not. The chances are that you have already come to believe that happiness

01:03:25.280 --> 01:03:30.620
is unattainable. But men have attained it, and they have attained it by

01:03:30.620 --> 01:03:35.820
realizing that happiness does not spring from the procuring of physical or mental

01:03:35.820 --> 01:03:41.120
pleasure, but from the development of reason and the adjustment of conduct to

01:03:41.120 --> 01:03:47.920
principles. I suppose that you will not have the audacity to deny this, and if

01:03:47.920 --> 01:03:53.220
you admit it, and still devote no part of your day to the deliberate consideration

01:03:53.220 --> 01:03:59.260
of your reason, principles, and conduct, you admit also that while striving for a

01:03:59.260 --> 01:04:04.860
certain thing you are regularly leaving undone the one act which is necessary to

01:04:04.860 --> 01:04:14.100
the attainment of that thing. Now, shall I blush, or will you? Do not fear that I

01:04:14.100 --> 01:04:19.760
mean to thrust certain principles upon your attention. I care not, in this place,

01:04:19.760 --> 01:04:24.720
what your principles are. Your principles may induce you to believe in the

01:04:24.720 --> 01:04:30.300
righteousness of burglary. I don't mind. All I urge is that a life in which

01:04:30.300 --> 01:04:36.280
conduct does not fairly well accord with principles is a silly life, and that

01:04:36.280 --> 01:04:40.940
conduct can only be made to accord with principles by means of daily

01:04:40.940 --> 01:04:47.700
examination, reflection, and resolution. What leads to the permanent sorrowfulness

01:04:47.700 --> 01:04:52.620
of burglars is that their principles are contrary to burglary. If they

01:04:52.620 --> 01:04:57.240
genuinely believed in the moral excellence of burglary, penal servitude

01:04:57.240 --> 01:05:03.000
would simply mean so many happy years for them. All martyrs are happy because

01:05:03.000 --> 01:05:09.940
their conduct and their principles agree. As for reason, which makes conduct and is

01:05:09.940 --> 01:05:14.960
not unconnected with the making of principles, it plays a far smaller part

01:05:14.960 --> 01:05:20.340
in our lives than we fancy. We are supposed to be reasonable, but we are much

01:05:20.340 --> 01:05:26.620
more instinctive than reasonable, and the less we reflect, the less reasonable we

01:05:26.620 --> 01:05:31.800
shall be. The next time you get cross with the waiter because your steak is

01:05:31.800 --> 01:05:37.440
overcooked, ask reason to step into the cabinet room of your mind and consult

01:05:37.440 --> 01:05:42.900
her. She will probably tell you that the waiter did not cook the steak and had no

01:05:42.900 --> 01:05:47.980
control over the cooking of the steak, and that even if he alone was to blame,

01:05:48.580 --> 01:05:53.500
you accomplished nothing good by getting cross, you merely lost your dignity,

01:05:54.180 --> 01:05:59.660
looked a fool in the eyes of sensible men, and soured the waiter while

01:05:59.660 --> 01:06:05.240
producing no effect whatever on the steak. The result of this consultation

01:06:05.240 --> 01:06:10.500
with reason, for which she makes no charge, will be that when once more your

01:06:10.500 --> 01:06:16.100
steak is overcooked you will treat the waiter as a fellow creature, remain quite

01:06:16.100 --> 01:06:22.320
calm in a kindly spirit, and politely insist on having a fresh steak. The gain

01:06:22.320 --> 01:06:28.340
will be obvious and solid. In the formation or modification of principles

01:06:28.340 --> 01:06:34.500
and the practice of conduct, much help can be derived from printed books issued

01:06:34.500 --> 01:06:39.020
at six pence each and upwards. I mentioned in my last chapter Marcus

01:06:39.020 --> 01:06:44.600
Aurelius and Epictetus. Certain even more widely known works will occur at

01:06:44.600 --> 01:06:51.740
once to the memory. I may also mention Pascal, La Prière, and Emerson. For

01:06:51.740 --> 01:06:57.540
myself you do not catch me travelling without my Marcus Aurelius. Yes, books

01:06:57.540 --> 01:07:02.620
are valuable, but not reading of books will take the place of a daily, candid,

01:07:03.080 --> 01:07:07.880
honest examination of what one has recently done and what one is about to

01:07:07.880 --> 01:07:13.780
do, of a steady looking at oneself in the face, disconcerting though the

01:07:13.780 --> 01:07:20.040
sight may be. When shall this important business be accomplished? The

01:07:20.040 --> 01:07:24.980
solitude of the evening journey home appears to me to be suitable for it. A

01:07:24.980 --> 01:07:28.680
reflective mood naturally follows the exertion of having earned the day's

01:07:28.680 --> 01:07:34.400
living. Of course if, instead of attending to an elementary and profoundly

01:07:34.400 --> 01:07:39.980
important duty, you prefer to read the paper, which you might just as well read

01:07:39.980 --> 01:07:45.840
while waiting for your dinner, I have nothing to say. But attend to it at some

01:07:45.840 --> 01:07:52.260
time of the day, you must. I now come to the evening hours. End of chapter.

01:08:19.280 --> 01:08:21.200
Interest in the Arts.

01:08:23.260 --> 01:08:28.940
Many people pursue a regular and uninterrupted course of idleness in the evenings because

01:08:28.940 --> 01:08:34.040
they think that there is no alternative to idleness but the study of literature, and

01:08:34.040 --> 01:08:36.840
they do not happen to have a taste for literature.

01:08:37.480 --> 01:08:39.320
This is a great mistake.

01:08:40.060 --> 01:08:46.480
Of course it is impossible, or at any rate very difficult, properly to study anything

01:08:46.740 --> 01:08:48.900
without the aid of printed books.

01:08:49.700 --> 01:08:55.660
But if you desire to understand the deeper depths of bridge or of boat sailing, you would

01:08:55.660 --> 01:09:00.000
not be deterred by your lack of interest in literature from reading the best books on

01:09:00.000 --> 01:09:01.540
bridge or boat sailing.

01:09:02.280 --> 01:09:08.260
We must therefore distinguish between literature and books treating of subjects not literary.

01:09:08.960 --> 01:09:11.260
I shall come to literature in due course.

01:09:12.040 --> 01:09:17.720
Let me now remark to those who have never read Meredith, and who are capable of being

01:09:17.720 --> 01:09:23.280
unmoved by a discussion as to whether Mr. Stephen Phillips is or is not a true poet,

01:09:23.840 --> 01:09:26.340
that they are perfectly within their rights.

01:09:27.020 --> 01:09:29.540
It is not a crime not to love literature.

01:09:30.340 --> 01:09:32.260
It is not a sign of imbecility.

01:09:33.100 --> 01:09:39.220
The mandarins of literature will order out to instant execution the unfortunate individual

01:09:39.220 --> 01:09:44.340
who does not comprehend, say, the influence of Wordsworth on Tennyson.

01:09:45.200 --> 01:09:47.300
But that is only their impudence.

01:09:47.720 --> 01:09:53.360
Where would they be, I wonder, if requested to explain the influences that went to make

01:09:53.360 --> 01:09:55.400
Tchaikovsky's Pathetic Symphony?

01:09:56.560 --> 01:10:02.260
There are enormous fields of knowledge quite outside literature which will yield magnificent

01:10:02.260 --> 01:10:03.820
results to cultivators.

01:10:04.460 --> 01:10:09.760
For example, since I have just mentioned the most popular piece of high-class music in

01:10:09.760 --> 01:10:15.160
England today, I am reminded that the promenade concerts begin in August.

01:10:15.720 --> 01:10:22.580
You go to them, you smoke your cigar or cigarette, and I regret to say that you strike your matches

01:10:22.580 --> 01:10:27.860
during the soft bars of the Lohengrin Overture, and you enjoy the music.

01:10:28.380 --> 01:10:34.440
But you say you cannot play the piano or the fiddle or even the banjo, that you know nothing

01:10:34.440 --> 01:10:35.100
of music.

01:10:35.980 --> 01:10:37.920
What does that matter?

01:10:38.700 --> 01:10:44.140
That you have a genuine taste for music is proved by the fact that, in order to fill

01:10:44.140 --> 01:10:50.260
his hall with you and your peers, the conductor is obliged to provide programs from which

01:10:50.260 --> 01:10:53.100
bad music is almost entirely excluded.

01:10:53.840 --> 01:10:56.180
A change from the old Covent Garden days.

01:10:56.880 --> 01:11:03.420
Now, surely your inability to perform the maiden's prayer on a piano need not prevent

01:11:03.420 --> 01:11:07.960
you from making yourself familiar with the construction of the orchestra to which you

01:11:07.960 --> 01:11:11.180
listen a couple of nights a week during a couple of months.

01:11:12.100 --> 01:11:18.320
As things are, you probably think of the orchestra as a heterogeneous mass of instruments producing

01:11:18.320 --> 01:11:21.500
a confused, agreeable mass of sound.

01:11:21.500 --> 01:11:27.500
You do not listen for details, because you have never trained your ears to listen to

01:11:27.500 --> 01:11:28.160
details.

01:11:29.160 --> 01:11:33.520
If you were asked to name the instruments which play the great theme at the beginning

01:11:33.520 --> 01:11:38.520
of the C-minor symphony, you could not name them for your life's sake.

01:11:39.120 --> 01:11:41.640
Yet you admire the C-minor symphony.

01:11:42.300 --> 01:11:43.880
It has thrilled you.

01:11:44.020 --> 01:11:45.540
It will thrill you again.

01:11:45.540 --> 01:11:50.440
You have even talked about it, in an expansive mood, to that lady.

01:11:50.940 --> 01:11:52.760
You know whom I mean.

01:11:53.600 --> 01:11:58.780
And all you can positively state about the C-minor symphony is that Beethoven composed

01:11:58.780 --> 01:12:01.640
it and that it is a jolly fine thing.

01:12:02.980 --> 01:12:09.980
Now, if you have read, say, Mr. Krebeel's How to Listen to Music, which can be got at

01:12:09.980 --> 01:12:14.800
any booksellers for less than the price of a stall at the Alhambra, and which contains

01:12:14.800 --> 01:12:19.680
photographs of all the orchestral instruments and plans of the arrangement of orchestras,

01:12:20.560 --> 01:12:26.040
you would next go to a promenade concert with an astonishing intensification of interest

01:12:26.040 --> 01:12:26.820
in it.

01:12:27.380 --> 01:12:33.720
Instead of a confused mass, the orchestra would appear to you as what it is, a marvelously

01:12:33.720 --> 01:12:39.480
balanced organism whose various groups of members each have a different and an indispensable

01:12:39.480 --> 01:12:40.160
function.

01:12:40.960 --> 01:12:45.920
You would spy out the instruments and listen for their respective sounds.

01:12:46.380 --> 01:12:50.500
You would know the gulf that separates a French horn from an English horn.

01:12:50.800 --> 01:12:55.940
And you would perceive why a player of the hautebois gets higher wages than a fiddler,

01:12:56.360 --> 01:12:58.880
though the fiddle is the more difficult instrument.

01:12:59.540 --> 01:13:06.000
You would live at a promenade concert, whereas previously you had merely existed there in

01:13:06.000 --> 01:13:10.740
a state of batific coma, like a baby gazing at a bright object.

01:13:11.860 --> 01:13:17.040
The foundations of a genuine, systematic knowledge of music might be laid.

01:13:17.820 --> 01:13:23.320
You might specialize your inquiries either on a particular form of music, such as the

01:13:23.320 --> 01:13:26.840
symphony, or on the works of a particular composer.

01:13:27.680 --> 01:13:33.680
At the end of a year of 48 weeks of three brief evenings each, combined with a study

01:13:33.680 --> 01:13:39.760
programs and attendances at concerts chosen out of your increasing knowledge, you would

01:13:39.760 --> 01:13:45.400
really know something about music, even though you were as far off as ever from jangling

01:13:45.400 --> 01:13:47.520
the maiden's prayer on the piano.

01:13:49.200 --> 01:13:52.200
But I hate music, you say.

01:13:52.900 --> 01:13:55.120
My dear sir, I respect you.

01:13:55.940 --> 01:13:59.160
What applies to music applies to the other arts.

01:13:59.520 --> 01:14:06.400
I might mention Mr. Claremont Witt's How to Look at Pictures, or Mr. Russell Sturges's

01:14:06.400 --> 01:14:12.820
How to Judge Architecture, as beginnings, mere beginnings, of systematic vitalizing

01:14:12.820 --> 01:14:17.880
knowledge in other arts, the materials for whose study abound in London.

01:14:18.580 --> 01:14:21.980
I hate all the arts, you say.

01:14:22.560 --> 01:14:25.480
My dear sir, I respect you more and more.

01:14:25.480 --> 01:14:30.280
I will deal with your case next, before coming to literature.

01:15:01.500 --> 01:15:08.420
Art is a great thing, but it is not the greatest. The most important of all

01:15:08.420 --> 01:15:14.160
perceptions is the continual perception of cause and effect. In other words, the

01:15:14.160 --> 01:15:19.220
perception of the continuous development of the universe. In still other words,

01:15:19.620 --> 01:15:24.200
the perception of the course of evolution. When one has thoroughly got

01:15:24.200 --> 01:15:29.520
imbued into one's head the leading truth that nothing happens without a cause, one

01:15:29.520 --> 01:15:35.180
grows not only large-minded, but large-hearted. It is hard to have one's

01:15:35.180 --> 01:15:40.200
watch stolen, but one reflects that the thief of the watch became a thief from

01:15:40.200 --> 01:15:44.740
causes of heredity and environment, which are as interesting as they are

01:15:44.740 --> 01:15:50.960
scientifically comprehensible. And one buys another watch, if not with joy, at

01:15:50.960 --> 01:15:59.500
any rate with a philosophy that makes bitterness impossible. One loses in the

01:15:59.500 --> 01:16:04.500
air which so many people have of being always shocked and pained by the

01:16:04.500 --> 01:16:10.020
curiousness of life. Such people live amid human nature as if human nature

01:16:10.020 --> 01:16:15.500
were a foreign country full of awful foreign customs. But having reached

01:16:15.500 --> 01:16:20.420
maturity, one ought surely to be ashamed of being a stranger in a strange

01:16:20.420 --> 01:16:26.980
land. The study of cause and effect, while it lessens the painfulness of

01:16:26.980 --> 01:16:33.060
life, adds to life's picturesqueness. The man to whom evolution is but a name

01:16:33.060 --> 01:16:38.700
looks at the sea as a grandiose monotonous spectacle, which he can witness

01:16:38.700 --> 01:16:43.520
in August for Three Schilling's third-class return. The man who is imbued

01:16:43.520 --> 01:16:49.280
with the idea of development, of continuous cause and effect, perceives in

01:16:49.280 --> 01:16:54.520
the sea an element which in the day before yesterday of geology was vapor,

01:16:54.520 --> 01:17:01.600
which yesterday was boiling and which tomorrow will inevitably be ice. He

01:17:01.600 --> 01:17:06.300
perceives that a liquid is merely something on its way to be solid, and he

01:17:06.300 --> 01:17:11.520
is penetrated by a sense of the tremendous changeful picturesqueness of

01:17:11.520 --> 01:17:16.420
life. Nothing will afford a more durable satisfaction than the constantly

01:17:16.420 --> 01:17:23.400
cultivated appreciation of this. This is the end of all science. Cause and effect

01:17:23.400 --> 01:17:29.580
are to be found everywhere. Rents went up in Shepherd's Bush. It was painful and

01:17:29.580 --> 01:17:34.360
shocking that rents should go up in Shepherd's Bush, but to a certain point

01:17:34.360 --> 01:17:39.620
we are all scientific students of cause and effect, and there was not a clerk

01:17:39.620 --> 01:17:43.760
lunching at a lion's restaurant who did not scientifically put two and two

01:17:43.760 --> 01:17:50.220
together and see in the once too penny tube the cause of an excessive demand

01:17:50.220 --> 01:17:55.700
for wigwams in Shepherd's Bush, and in the excessive demand for wigwams the

01:17:55.700 --> 01:18:01.840
cause of the increase in the price of wigwams. Simple, you say disdainfully.

01:18:02.680 --> 01:18:08.800
Everything, the whole complex movement of the universe, is as simple as that when

01:18:08.800 --> 01:18:14.280
you can sufficiently put two and two together, and my dear sir, perhaps you

01:18:14.280 --> 01:18:19.800
happen to be an estate agent's clerk and you hate the arts and you want to foster

01:18:19.800 --> 01:18:23.920
your immortal soul and you can't be interested in your business because it's

01:18:23.920 --> 01:18:31.140
so humdrum. Nothing is humdrum. The tremendous changeful picturesqueness of

01:18:31.140 --> 01:18:37.220
life is marvelously shown in an estate agent's office. What? There was a block

01:18:37.220 --> 01:18:42.420
of traffic in Oxford Street. To avoid the block people actually began to travel

01:18:42.420 --> 01:18:47.300
under the cellars and drains, and the result was a rise of rents in Shepherd's

01:18:47.300 --> 01:18:53.680
Bush. And you say that isn't picturesque? Suppose you were to study, in this

01:18:53.680 --> 01:18:58.000
spirit, the property question in London for an hour and a half every other

01:18:58.000 --> 01:19:02.880
evening. Would it not give zest to your business and transform your whole

01:19:02.880 --> 01:19:08.360
life? You would arrive at more difficult problems, and you would be able to

01:19:08.360 --> 01:19:13.820
tell us why, as the natural result of cause and effect, the longest straight

01:19:13.820 --> 01:19:19.460
street in London is about a yard and a half in length, while the longest

01:19:19.460 --> 01:19:25.480
absolutely straight street in Paris extends for miles. I think you will admit

01:19:25.480 --> 01:19:30.220
that in an estate agent's clerk I have not chosen an example that especially

01:19:30.220 --> 01:19:36.340
favors my theories. You are a bank clerk, and you have not read that

01:19:36.340 --> 01:19:42.360
breathless romance disguised as a scientific study, Walter Beghot's

01:19:42.360 --> 01:19:48.460
Lombard Street? Ah, my dear sir, if you had begun with that and followed it up

01:19:48.460 --> 01:19:53.480
for 90 minutes every other evening, how enthralling your business would be to

01:19:53.480 --> 01:20:00.620
you, and how much more clearly you would understand human nature. You are penned

01:20:00.620 --> 01:20:05.420
in town, but you love excursions in the country and the observation of

01:20:05.420 --> 01:20:11.180
wildlife, certainly a heart-enlarging diversion. Why don't you walk out of

01:20:11.180 --> 01:20:16.080
your house door, in your slippers, to the nearest gas-lamp of a night with

01:20:16.080 --> 01:20:21.000
a butterfly net, and observe the wildlife of common and rare moths that

01:20:21.000 --> 01:20:26.040
is beating about it, and coordinate the knowledge thus obtained, and build

01:20:26.040 --> 01:20:31.280
a superstructure on it, and at last get to know something about something?

01:20:31.280 --> 01:20:38.220
You need not be devoted to the arts, not to literature, in order to live fully.

01:20:39.160 --> 01:20:43.680
The whole field of daily habit and seeing is waiting to satisfy that

01:20:43.680 --> 01:20:48.820
curiosity which means life, and the satisfaction of which means an

01:20:48.820 --> 01:20:55.360
understanding heart. I promised to deal with your case, O man who hates art and

01:20:55.360 --> 01:21:00.900
literature, and I have dealt with it. I now come to the case of the person

01:21:00.900 --> 01:21:07.000
happily very common, who does like reading. End of chapter.

01:21:39.760 --> 01:21:46.080
Novels are excluded from serious reading, so that the man who, bent on self-improvement,

01:21:46.480 --> 01:21:51.220
has been deciding to devote ninety minutes three times a week to a complete study of

01:21:51.220 --> 01:21:55.780
the works of Charles Dickens would be well advised to alter his plans.

01:21:56.880 --> 01:21:59.980
The reason is not that novels are not serious.

01:22:00.640 --> 01:22:04.180
Some of the great literature of the world is in the form of prose fiction.

01:22:04.820 --> 01:22:11.100
The reason is that bad novels ought not to be read, and that good novels never demand

01:22:11.100 --> 01:22:14.440
any appreciable mental application on the part of the reader.

01:22:15.340 --> 01:22:19.120
It is only the bad parts of Meredith's novels that are difficult.

01:22:19.960 --> 01:22:25.240
A good novel rushes you forward like a skiff down a stream, and you arrive at the end,

01:22:25.520 --> 01:22:28.240
perhaps breathless, but unexhausted.

01:22:29.120 --> 01:22:32.320
The best novels involve the least strain.

01:22:33.100 --> 01:22:38.960
Now, in the cultivation of the mind, one of the most important factors is precisely the

01:22:38.960 --> 01:22:45.400
feeling of strain, of difficulty, of a task which one part of you is anxious to achieve,

01:22:45.860 --> 01:22:48.400
and another part of you is anxious to shirk.

01:22:48.900 --> 01:22:52.000
And that feeling cannot be got in facing a novel.

01:22:52.700 --> 01:22:56.940
You do not set your teeth in order to read Anna Karenina.

01:22:57.800 --> 01:23:03.380
Therefore, though you should read novels, you should not read them in those ninety minutes.

01:23:04.900 --> 01:23:08.920
Imaginative poetry produces a far greater mental strain than novels.

01:23:09.420 --> 01:23:13.160
It produces probably the severest strain of any form of literature.

01:23:13.980 --> 01:23:16.300
It is the highest form of literature.

01:23:17.000 --> 01:23:21.900
It yields the highest form of pleasure, and teaches the highest form of wisdom.

01:23:22.700 --> 01:23:26.220
In a word, there is nothing to compare with it.

01:23:26.220 --> 01:23:32.880
I say this with sad consciousness of the fact that the majority of people do not read poetry.

01:23:33.340 --> 01:23:38.420
I am persuaded that many excellent persons, if they were confronted with the alternatives

01:23:38.420 --> 01:23:44.560
of reading Paradise Lost, and going round Trafalgar Square at noonday on their knees

01:23:44.560 --> 01:23:48.920
in sackcloth, would choose the ordeal of public ridicule.

01:23:49.680 --> 01:23:56.480
Still, I will never cease advising my friends and enemies to read poetry before anything.

01:23:57.580 --> 01:24:04.500
If poetry is what is called a sealed book to you, begin by reading Haslett's famous essay on the

01:24:04.500 --> 01:24:10.980
nature of poetry in general. It is the best thing of its kind in English, and no one who has read

01:24:10.980 --> 01:24:18.020
it can possibly be under the misapprehension that poetry is a medieval torture, or a mad elephant,

01:24:18.020 --> 01:24:25.280
or a gun that will go off by itself and kill it forty paces. Indeed, it is difficult to imagine

01:24:25.280 --> 01:24:31.720
the mental state of the man who, after reading Haslett's essay, is not urgently desirous of

01:24:31.720 --> 01:24:38.840
reading some poetry before his next meal. If the essay so inspires you, I would suggest that you

01:24:38.840 --> 01:24:46.040
make a commencement with purely narrative poetry. There is an infinitely finer English novel,

01:24:46.040 --> 01:24:52.440
written by a woman, than anything by George Eliot or the Brontes, or even Jane Austen,

01:24:52.660 --> 01:25:00.620
which perhaps you have not read. Its title is Aurora Lee, and its author E. B. Browning.

01:25:01.160 --> 01:25:06.900
It happens to be written in verse, and to contain a considerable amount of genuinely fine poetry.

01:25:07.840 --> 01:25:14.420
Decide to read that book through, even if you die for it. Forget that it is fine poetry,

01:25:14.420 --> 01:25:21.740
read it simply for the story and the social ideas, and when you have done, ask yourself honestly

01:25:21.740 --> 01:25:29.280
whether you still dislike poetry. I have known more than one person to whom Aurora Lee has been

01:25:29.280 --> 01:25:35.020
the means of proving that, in assuming they hated poetry, they were entirely mistaken.

01:25:36.120 --> 01:25:42.000
Of course, if, after Haslett, and such an experiment made in the light of Haslett,

01:25:42.000 --> 01:25:47.500
you are finally assured that there is something in you which is antagonistic to poetry,

01:25:48.100 --> 01:25:54.820
you must be content with history or philosophy. I shall regret it, yet not inconsolably.

01:25:55.540 --> 01:26:02.100
The decline in fall is not to be named in the same day with Paradise Lost, but it is a vastly

01:26:02.100 --> 01:26:08.160
pretty thing, and Herbert Spencer's First Principles simply laughs at the claims of

01:26:08.160 --> 01:26:13.940
poetry, and refuses to be accepted as ought but the most majestic product of any human mind.

01:26:14.820 --> 01:26:20.200
I do not suggest that either of these works is suitable for a tyro in mental strains,

01:26:20.840 --> 01:26:27.340
but I see no reason why any man of average intelligence should not, after a year of

01:26:27.340 --> 01:26:34.180
continuous reading, be fit to assault the supreme masterpieces of history or philosophy.

01:26:34.980 --> 01:26:41.000
The great convenience of masterpieces is that they are so astonishingly lucid.

01:26:42.100 --> 01:26:48.820
I suggest no particular work as a start. The attempt would be futile in the space of my command,

01:26:49.440 --> 01:26:52.900
but I have two general suggestions of a certain importance.

01:26:53.840 --> 01:27:00.380
The first is to define the direction and scope of your efforts. Choose a limited period,

01:27:00.380 --> 01:27:07.960
or a limited subject, or a single author. Say to yourself, I will know something about the French

01:27:07.960 --> 01:27:17.140
Revolution, or the rise of railways, or the works of John Keats. And during a given period,

01:27:17.380 --> 01:27:24.320
to be settled beforehand, confine yourself to your choice. There is much pleasure to be derived from

01:27:24.320 --> 01:27:32.320
being a specialist. The second suggestion is to think as well as to read. I know people who read

01:27:32.320 --> 01:27:37.580
and read, and for all the good it does them they might just as well cut bread and butter.

01:27:38.580 --> 01:27:44.780
They take to reading as better men take to drink. They fly through the shires of literature on a

01:27:44.780 --> 01:27:51.300
motor-car, their sole object being motion. They will tell you how many books they have read in a

01:27:51.300 --> 01:27:57.620
year. Unless you give at least forty-five minutes to careful, fatiguing reflection,

01:27:58.220 --> 01:28:04.940
it is an awful bore at first. Upon what you are reading, your ninety minutes of a night are chiefly

01:28:04.940 --> 01:28:13.660
wasted. This means that your pace will be slow. Never mind. Forget the goal, think only of the

01:28:13.660 --> 01:28:20.460
surrounding country, and after a period, perhaps when you least expect it, you will suddenly find

01:28:20.460 --> 01:28:25.920
yourself in a lovely town on a hill. End of chapter

01:28:56.040 --> 01:28:59.300
DANGERS TO AVOID.

01:29:00.420 --> 01:29:06.280
I cannot terminate these hints, often, I fear, too didactic and abrupt, upon the full

01:29:06.280 --> 01:29:11.860
use of one's time to the great end of living, as distinguished from vegetating, without

01:29:11.860 --> 01:29:17.080
briefly referring to certain dangers which lie in wait for the sincere aspirant towards

01:29:17.080 --> 01:29:17.660
life.

01:29:18.740 --> 01:29:24.820
The first is the terrible danger of becoming that most odious and least supportable of persons,

01:29:25.360 --> 01:29:26.180
a prig.

01:29:27.000 --> 01:29:31.360
Now a prig is a pert fellow who gives himself heirs of superior wisdom.

01:29:32.180 --> 01:29:37.540
A prig is a pompous fool who has gone out for a ceremonial walk, and without knowing

01:29:37.540 --> 01:29:42.900
it has lost an important part of his attire, namely, his sense of humour.

01:29:43.960 --> 01:29:51.700
A prig is a tedious individual who, having made a discovery, is so impressed by his discovery

01:29:51.700 --> 01:29:57.740
that he is capable of being gravely displeased because the entire world is not also impressed

01:29:57.740 --> 01:29:58.960
by it.

01:29:59.580 --> 01:30:04.800
Unconsciously to become a prig is an easy and a fatal thing.

01:30:06.060 --> 01:30:11.940
Hence, when one sets forth on the enterprise of using all one's time, it is just as well

01:30:11.940 --> 01:30:18.040
to remember that one's own time, and not other people's time, is the material with

01:30:18.040 --> 01:30:19.480
which one has to deal.

01:30:20.040 --> 01:30:25.600
That the earth rolled on pretty comfortably before one began to balance a budget of the

01:30:25.600 --> 01:30:31.500
hours, and that it will continue to roll on pretty comfortably whether or not one succeeds

01:30:31.500 --> 01:30:35.800
in one's new role of Chancellor of the Exchequer of Time.

01:30:36.740 --> 01:30:43.140
It is as well not to chatter too much about what one is doing, and not to betray a too

01:30:43.140 --> 01:30:49.600
pained sadness at the spectacle of a whole world deliberately wasting so many hours out

01:30:49.600 --> 01:30:52.880
of every day, and therefore never really living.

01:30:53.660 --> 01:31:00.100
It will be found, ultimately, that in taking care of one's self, one has quite all one

01:31:00.100 --> 01:31:00.760
can do.

01:31:02.240 --> 01:31:07.840
Another danger is the danger of being tied to a programme like a slave to a chariot.

01:31:08.660 --> 01:31:11.820
One's programme must not be allowed to run away with one.

01:31:12.340 --> 01:31:16.960
It must be respected, but it must not be worshipped as a fetish.

01:31:17.600 --> 01:31:20.980
A programme of daily employ is not a religion.

01:31:22.540 --> 01:31:28.980
This seems obvious, yet I know men whose lives are a burden to themselves, and a distressing

01:31:28.980 --> 01:31:34.420
burden to their relatives and friends, simply because they have failed to appreciate the

01:31:34.420 --> 01:31:34.940
obvious.

01:31:35.900 --> 01:31:43.000
Oh, no, I have heard the martyred wife exclaim, Arthur always takes the dog out for exercise

01:31:43.000 --> 01:31:47.300
at eight o'clock, and he always begins to read at a quarter to nine.

01:31:47.760 --> 01:31:52.620
So it's quite out of the question that we should, etc., etc.

01:31:53.340 --> 01:31:59.960
And the note of absolute finality in that plaintive voice reveals the unsuspected and

01:31:59.960 --> 01:32:01.980
ridiculous tragedy of a career.

01:32:03.260 --> 01:32:09.940
On the other hand, a programme is a programme, and unless it is treated with deference, it

01:32:09.940 --> 01:32:12.260
ceases to be anything but a poor joke.

01:32:13.420 --> 01:32:18.760
To treat one's programme with exactly the right amount of deference, to live with not

01:32:18.760 --> 01:32:25.500
too much and not too little elasticity, is scarcely the simple affair it may appear to

01:32:25.500 --> 01:32:26.700
the inexperienced.

01:32:27.600 --> 01:32:34.240
And still another danger is the danger of developing a policy of rush, of being gradually

01:32:34.240 --> 01:32:38.340
more and more obsessed by what one has to do next.

01:32:39.020 --> 01:32:45.460
In this way one may come to exist as in a prison, and one's life may cease to be one's

01:32:45.460 --> 01:32:45.780
own.

01:32:46.500 --> 01:32:56.680
One may take the dog out for a walk at eight o'clock, and meditate the whole time on the

01:32:59.180 --> 01:33:04.700
And the occasional deliberate breaking of one's programme will not help to mend matters.

01:33:05.580 --> 01:33:11.580
The evil springs not from persisting without elasticity in what one has attempted, but

01:33:11.580 --> 01:33:17.540
from originally attempting too much, from filling one's programme till it runs over.

01:33:18.380 --> 01:33:23.300
The only cure is to reconstitute the programme and to attempt less.

01:33:23.980 --> 01:33:30.460
But the appetite for knowledge grows by what it feeds on, and there are men who come to

01:33:30.460 --> 01:33:33.680
like a constant breathless hurry of endeavour.

01:33:34.420 --> 01:33:40.500
Of them it may be said that a constant breathless hurry is better than an eternal dose.

01:33:41.880 --> 01:33:48.960
In any case, if the programme exhibits a tendency to be oppressive, and yet one wishes not to

01:33:48.960 --> 01:33:55.340
it, an excellent palliative is to pass with exaggerated deliberation from one portion

01:33:55.340 --> 01:34:02.320
of it to another, for example, to spend five minutes in perfect mental quiescence between

01:34:02.840 --> 01:34:05.580
chaining up the St. Bernard and opening the book.

01:34:06.220 --> 01:34:11.960
In other words, to waste five minutes with the entire consciousness of wasting them.

01:34:12.960 --> 01:34:19.780
The last, and chiefest danger which I would indicate, is one to which I have already referred,

01:34:20.380 --> 01:34:23.600
the risk of a failure at the commencement of the enterprise.

01:34:24.280 --> 01:34:26.520
I must insist on it.

01:34:27.360 --> 01:34:33.100
A failure at the commencement may easily kill outright the new-born impulse towards a complete

01:34:33.100 --> 01:34:38.260
vitality, and therefore every precaution should be observed to avoid it.

01:34:38.780 --> 01:34:42.020
The impulse must not be overtaxed.

01:34:42.240 --> 01:34:48.680
Let the pace of the first lap be absurdly slow, but let it be as regular as possible.

01:34:49.900 --> 01:34:56.600
And having once decided to achieve a certain task, achieve it at all costs of tedium and

01:34:56.600 --> 01:34:57.260
distaste.

01:34:58.320 --> 01:35:03.140
The gain in self-confidence of having accomplished a tiresome labour is immense.

01:35:04.240 --> 01:35:10.740
Finally, in choosing the first occupations of those evening hours, be guided by nothing

01:35:10.740 --> 01:35:14.120
whatever but your taste and natural inclination.

01:35:14.980 --> 01:35:19.280
It is a fine thing to be a walking encyclopedia of philosophy.

01:35:20.000 --> 01:35:25.620
But if you happen to have no liking for philosophy, and to have a like for the natural history

01:35:25.620 --> 01:35:32.020
of street-cries, much better leave philosophy alone and take to street-cries.

01:35:35.820 --> 01:35:36.500
End of book.

01:35:37.480 --> 01:35:38.340
Thank you for listening.
